or any other religion-specific prayer) was banned from being a school-wide activity; it was usually a part of a school's daily opening exercises. That is not the case here. If a group of Christian students, or Jewish students want to hold a private activity at lunch hour or whenever it doesn't interfere with classes, that's fine, too. Atheists can hold their meetings also. (What would they talk about?) &#10;Kudos to those who see this issue of little significance in the big picture of life. This protest sounds more like the expression of basic red-neck prejudice. What a shame. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="883" language="en" documentId="1349" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="k.alan" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tempers-flare-over-prayer-in-schools-1.1104775" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1349" notes="" title="Tempers flare over prayer in schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="74"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="75" end="709"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="710" end="883"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>